            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the soil texture triangle works</h2>
              <p>
                The USDA soil texture triangle is a ternary diagram that
                classifies mineral soils based on the relative proportions of
                <strong>sand</strong>, <strong>silt</strong>, and
                <strong>clay</strong>. Each corner of the triangle represents
                100% of one particle-size fraction and 0% of the others.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Basic requirements:</p>
                <ul class="list-disc pl-5 mb-0">
                  <li>Sand (%) + Silt (%) + Clay (%) = 100%</li>
                  <li>Each fraction must be between 0 and 100%</li>
                  <li>
                    Values usually come from a lab texture analysis (e.g.,
                    hydrometer or pipette method)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>From percentages to a point on the triangle</h3>
              <p>
                Mathematically, the three percentages form a point in a 2D
                coordinate system. In this calculator we convert sand–silt–clay
                to Cartesian coordinates using barycentric coordinates on an
                equilateral triangle:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="mb-1"><strong>Vertices (in pixels)</strong></p>
                <ul class="mb-2">
                  <li>Sand vertex \(S = (220, 200)\)</li>
                  <li>Clay vertex \(C = (20, 200)\)</li>
                  <li>Silt vertex \(Si = (120, 20)\)</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mb-1"><strong>Point position</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Let \(s, si, c\) be sand, silt, and clay fractions (0–1). Then
                  the point \(P\) is:
                </p>
                <p>\(P = s \cdot S + si \cdot Si + c \cdot C\)</p>
              </div>

              <h2>USDA soil texture classes used in this calculator</h2>
              <p>
                This tool follows the USDA NRCS soil texture triangle and
                returns one of the standard texture classes. The most common
                classes and their typical properties are summarized below.
              </p>

