                        ~50–70% sand, 10–20% clay
                      </td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">
                        Good tilth, moderate water holding, easy to work.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b font-medium">Loam</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">
                        ~40% sand, 40% silt, 20% clay
                      </td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">
                        Balanced properties; often considered “ideal” for many
                        crops.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b font-medium">Silt loam</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">
                        50–80% silt, 0–27% clay
                      </td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">
                        High water-holding, can crust and compact if mismanaged.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b font-medium">Clay loam</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">
                        27–40% clay, moderate sand and silt
                      </td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">
                        Good nutrient retention, slower drainage, can be sticky
                        when wet.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b font-medium">Clay</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">≥ 40% clay</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">
                        High water and nutrient holding, poor drainage, prone to
                        shrinking and swelling.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>

              <h2>Step-by-step: determining soil texture</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Obtain sand, silt, and clay percentages from a lab or field
                  method.
                </li>
                <li>Enter the three values in the calculator.</li>
                <li>Ensure they sum to 100% (or enable normalization).</li>
                <li>Click <strong>Classify Soil Texture</strong>.</li>
                <li>
                  Read the texture class and interpretation, and view the point
                  on the triangle.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Field vs. laboratory texture</h3>
              <p>
                Laboratory methods (e.g., hydrometer, pipette) provide the most
                accurate particle-size distribution. Field methods such as the
                “ribbon test” can give a quick estimate but are less precise.
                This calculator assumes you are using quantitative percentages.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and notes</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The USDA triangle applies to mineral soils; organic soils
                  (peats, mucks) are classified differently.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Gravel and coarse fragments are usually excluded from the
                  sand–silt–clay percentages.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Management decisions should consider structure, organic
                  matter, and depth in addition to texture.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>What if my values add up to 99% or 101%?</h3>
              <p>
                Small rounding errors are common. You can either adjust one
                fraction manually or enable the
                <strong>normalize</strong> option, which rescales all three
                values so they sum to exactly 100% while preserving their
                ratios.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Can I use this for FAO or other international texture systems?
              </h3>
              <p>
                This tool is based on the USDA soil texture triangle. Many
                countries use similar but not identical systems. For most
                practical purposes the USDA classes are close enough, but for
                regulatory or research work you should confirm which
                classification system is required.
              </p>

              <h3>How does texture affect irrigation and fertilization?</h3>
              <p>
                Coarse-textured (sandy) soils need smaller, more frequent
                irrigation and lighter fertilizer doses because they drain
                quickly and leach nutrients. Fine-textured (clayey) soils can
                hold more water and nutrients but may require careful management
                to avoid waterlogging and compaction.
              </p>
            </section>
